# Virtual Threads — Revision Notes

**Problem with Platform Threads**
- 1:1 mapping with OS thread, ~1MB stack, OS scheduler, context switch costly
- OS handle kar sakta hai sirf kuch hazaar threads → thread-per-request model scale nahi karta

**Virtual Thread = JVM-managed lightweight thread**
- M:N model — lakhs of virtual threads, few **carrier threads** (platform threads, usually = CPU cores, ForkJoinPool)
- Stack = JVM heap me, few KB, dynamically grows

**Core Mechanism — Unmount/Remount**
- Blocking call (DB, network, file I/O) → virtual thread carrier se **unmount**, carrier free ho ke doosra virtual thread serve karta hai
- I/O complete → virtual thread kisi bhi free carrier pe **remount**
- Ye sab JVM ke andar hota hai, koi OS call nahi

**Pinning (catch)**
- `synchronized` block ke andar blocking call, ya native/JNI call ke andar block → unmount nahi ho pata, carrier thread block ho jata hai
- Fix: `synchronized` → `ReentrantLock` use karo

**Java Thread vs OS Thread**
- Platform thread: Java Thread object ↔ OS thread — permanent 1:1
- Virtual thread: Java Thread object ↔ OS thread — temporary, sirf mounted state ke time

**Kab fayda, kab nahi**
- **I/O-bound / high blocking frequency** → massive benefit (DB calls, API calls, file I/O) — carrier thread reuse hota hai
- **CPU-bound / no blocking** → koi fayda nahi, virtual thread = platform thread performance-wise, kyunki unmount ka mauka hi nahi milta
- Concurrency limit CPU-bound case me phir bhi core count se bound rehta hai

**Mixed Example (real world common)**
```java
public Report generateReport(String userId) {
    List<Data> rawData = fetchDataFromDB(userId);   // Blocking I/O → unmount fayda
    Report report = computeAggregations(rawData);    // CPU-bound → no fayda
    saveReportToS3(report);                            // Blocking I/O → unmount fayda
    return report;
}
```
Net benefit tab bhi milta hai kyunki typical apps me I/O wait time >> compute time.

**One-liner**
> I/O-bound workload → virtual threads. CPU-bound workload → traditional fixed-size platform thread pool (matched to core count).




# Java Version-wise Key Features — Revision Notes

## Java 11 → HTTP Client API

**Purpose:** Old `HttpURLConnection` bahut clunky tha (verbose, no HTTP/2 support, blocking-only). Java 11 me naya **standardized `java.net.http.HttpClient`** aaya.

**Fayda:**
- **HTTP/2 support** built-in (multiplexing — ek connection pe multiple requests parallel)
- **Both sync aur async** APIs (`send()` for blocking, `sendAsync()` for non-blocking using `CompletableFuture`)
- Clean, fluent **builder-style API** — request/response banana easy
- WebSocket support bhi built-in
- JSON/REST APIs call karna bahut simpler ho gaya bina external library (jaise Apache HttpClient) ke

```java
HttpClient client = HttpClient.newHttpClient();
HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
        .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/data"))
        .build();
HttpResponse<String> response = client.send(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());
```

**One-liner:** Modern, HTTP/2-ready, sync+async client — bina third-party library ke REST calls karne ke liye.

---

## Java 17 → Records

**Easy definition:** Record ek **immutable data class** hai jisme boilerplate (constructor, getters, `equals`, `hashCode`, `toString`) compiler khud generate karta hai — sirf data hold karne ke liye.

```java
public record Point(int x, int y) { }
```
Ye automatically `x()`, `y()` getters, constructor, `equals`, `hashCode`, `toString` bana deta hai.

**Fayda:** DTOs/value objects likhne me time aur boilerplate dono bachta hai. Fields `final` hote hain (immutable).

---

## Java 17 → Sealed Classes

**Easy definition:** Sealed class tumhe control karne deti hai ki **kaun-kaun si classes** tumhari class ko extend kar sakti hain — restricted/controlled inheritance.

```java
public sealed class Shape permits Circle, Square { }
public final class Circle extends Shape { }
public final class Square extends Shape { }
```

**Fayda:** 
- Inheritance hierarchy **closed aur predictable** rehti hai (koi random class extend nahi kar sakti)
- Pattern matching (`switch`) ke sath combine hoke **exhaustive checking** milti hai bina `default` case likhe — compiler ko pata hota hai total kitne subtypes hain

**One-liner:** Enums ka powerful version — jaha har case apna alag data/behavior rakh sake.

